# Spec-Driven Development — MANDATORY

## Active Specs

- `docs/specs/roadmap.md` — **Product Roadmap** (high-level sub-project breakdown, dependencies, status)
- `docs/specs/2026-05-30-core-platform-design.md` — SP1: Core Platform (auth, profiles, groups) -- COMPLETE
- `docs/specs/2026-05-30-real-time-coordination-design.md` — SP2: Real-Time Coordination (WebSocket transport, presence, Redis fan-out, session/event contracts) -- PLANNED

## BLOCKER: Spec Update Gate

> **This is a BLOCKER, not a nice-to-have. You MUST NOT finish a response that contains code changes without also updating specs if applicable. Treat a missing spec update the same as a compilation error — the task is NOT done.**

### Pre-flight (BEFORE writing any code)

1. Read the relevant spec section(s) to understand the current contract
2. If no spec exists for the feature area, tell the user and create one before coding
3. When starting a new sub-project, read `docs/specs/roadmap.md` for scope and dependencies
4. When working on realtime transport, presence, session scheduling, Redis pub/sub, or WS event contracts, read the SP2 realtime spec before coding

### Post-flight (BEFORE saying "done", restarting app, or ending your response)

Run this checklist on EVERY response that touches code:

1. **Did I change any of these?**
   - API endpoint (added, removed, renamed, changed method/params)
   - Database column or table
   - Freezed model field (added, removed, renamed)
   - Pydantic schema field
   - Navigation structure or routing (routes added, moved, nested)
   - User flow (new screen, changed flow order, new interaction pattern)
   - UI component (new shared widget, changed component behavior/API)
   - Architecture pattern (storage strategy, auth flow, state management)
   - Config or infrastructure

2. **If YES to any → update specs in THIS SAME response:**
   - Bump `version` in the spec front-matter
   - Update the relevant section(s)
   - Add a Change Log entry: `| date | section | what changed | why |`
   - If the change affects the roadmap (sub-project status, new deliverables), update `roadmap.md` too

3. **If NO to all → no spec update needed** (pure bug fix, style-only tweak, lint fix, test addition)

### Enforcement Triggers

If you are about to write code that touches ANY of these, STOP and plan the spec update alongside:

- `models/`, `schemas.py` → data model change
- `routes.py`, `app_router.dart`, `route_names.dart` → navigation/API change
- `*_screen.dart`, `*_provider.dart` → user flow change
- `shared/widgets/` → new/changed shared component
- `glass_components.dart`, `app_theme.dart` → design system change
- `*_repository.dart` → data layer contract change
- `deploy/`, `docker-compose.yml` → infrastructure change

### What Does NOT Require a Spec Update

- Bug fixes that don't change the API contract, data model, or navigation
- Internal refactors that don't affect the public interface
- Dependency version bumps
- Test additions
- Pure styling changes (colors, spacing, font sizes) that don't add new components
- Lint fixes

## Spec File Conventions

- One spec per sub-project, named `docs/specs/YYYY-MM-DD-<name>.md`
- Front-matter: `spec`, `version`, `status`, `last_updated`, `sub_project`
- Bump version on every update (semver patch for small changes, minor for structural)
- Change Log at the bottom, newest entries last
- Cross-reference the roadmap from each spec and vice versa
